President Joe Biden has announced his intent to nominate several individuals to serve as Republican members of boards and commissions that require bipartisan membership. The nominees are as follows:

1. Andrew N. Ferguson: Nominee for Commissioner of the Federal Trade Commission. He currently serves as the Solicitor General of the Commonwealth of Virginia and has extensive experience in appellate litigation, representing clients before the Supreme Court and federal courts of appeals.

2. Melissa Holyoak: Nominee for Commissioner of the Federal Trade Commission. She is currently the Utah Solicitor General, where she manages various divisions, including antitrust and data privacy.

3. Henry J. Kerner: Nominee for Member of the Merit Systems Protection Board. He has been serving as the Special Counsel of the U.S. Office of Special Counsel since 2017 and has implemented new processes to increase responsiveness to whistleblower complaints.

4. Amanda Wood Laihow: Nominee for Member of the Occupational Safety and Health Review Commission. She currently serves as a Commissioner on the Occupational Safety and Health Review Commission and has extensive experience in labor and employment policy.

5. Elliott Abrams: Nominee for Member of the United States Advisory Commission on Public Diplomacy. He is a senior fellow for Middle Eastern Studies at the Council on Foreign Relations and has held various positions in public service, including serving in the State Department as Special Representative for Iran and Special Representative for Venezuela.

6. Jamie Fly: Nominee for Member of the International Broadcasting Advisory Board, United States Agency for Global Media. He previously served as President and CEO of Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty and has experience in foreign policy and national security affairs.

7. Laura Dove: Nominee for Trustee of the James Madison Memorial Fellowship Foundation. She is currently the Senior Director for Administration at the Harvard Kennedy School's Institute of Politics and has over 20 years of experience working for the U.S. Senate.

8. Bradford P. Wilson: Nominee for Trustee of the James Madison Memorial Fellowship Foundation. He is the Executive Director of the James Madison Program in American Ideals and Institutions at Princeton University and has expertise in American constitutional law and political thought.

These nominations reflect President Biden's commitment to including bipartisan representation in various boards and commissions.